The 3-month prevalence rate was 71{\%} for any pain, 47{\%} for recurrent pain, 55{\%} for pain at multiple ($\geq$2) locations and 27{\%} for recurrent pain at multiple locations. Headache and abdominal pain were the most frequently reported (44.2{\%}, 40.8{\%}) either as recurrent (22.8{\%}, 20.3{\%}) or as the most bothersome pain (MBP) (19.6{\%}, 14.7{\%}). Children from immigrant vs. non-immigrant families and children from lower vs. upper social-class families showed significantly higher prevalence rates for tooth (14{\%} vs. 10{\%}), lower abdomen (10{\%} vs. 7{\%}), chest (9{\%} vs. 7{\%}), arm (9{\%} vs. 6{\%}) and eye pain (9{\%} vs. 5{\%}). Of children with repeated MBP, only 10{\%} of them used medications or consulted a doctor about the pain 'often/always,' while the majority of them did not act at all. In general, older age groups, females, poor health status and urban residence were associated with pain in children.

